 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|23}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.37&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|15}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.70&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|-\n| 2015<ref name=\"BRW2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.afr.com/leadership/brw-lists/brw-rich-200-list-2015-20160303-gn98ff|title=BRW Rich 200 List 2015 |work=[[Financial Review]] |date=May 2015 |accessdate=9 June 2016 |editor=Stensholt, John |location=Australia }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/australia-billionaires/list/#tab:overall|title=2015 Australia's 50 Richest|accessdate=10 June 2015|work=Forbes Asia|date=March 2015 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|21}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.75&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|15}} {{steady}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.90&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|-\n| 2016<ref name=\"Forbes2016\"/><ref name=BRW2016>{{cite journal|url=http://www.afr.com/leadership/brw-lists/brw-rich-200-list-2016-20160526-gp4ejn|title=BRW Rich 200 list 2016 |journal=[[Financial Review]]|location=Australia|date=27 May 2016|accessdate=9 June 2016|editor=Stensholt, John}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|37}} {{decrease}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.32&nbsp;billion {{decrease}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|13}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.80&nbsp;billion {{decrease}}\n|-\n| 2017<ref name=\"BRW2017\">{{cite news |url=https://www.afr.com/leadership/afr-lists/rich-list/financial-review-rich-list-2017-20170525-gwcvr6|title=BRW Rich 200 List 2017 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/australia-billionaires/list/#tab:overall_search:hintze|title=2017 Australia's 50 Richest|accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|24}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.98&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|17}} {{decrease}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $2.3&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|-\n| 2018<ref name=\"AFR2018\">{{cite news |url=https://www.afr.com/brand/afr-magazine/rich-list-overview-20180413-h0yqo5|title=AFR Rich List 2018 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/australia-billionaires/list/#tab:overall_search:hintze|title=2017 Australia's 50 Richest|accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|22}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $2.56&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|}\n{{column}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|<small>Legend</small>\n|-\n!<small> Icon</small>\n!<small> Description</small>\n|-\n|{{steady}}\n|<small>Has not changed from the previous year</small>\n|-\n|{{profit}}\n|<small>Has increased from the previous year</small>\n|-\n|{{loss}}\n|<small>Has decreased from the previous year</small>\n|}\n{{columns-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hintze, Michael}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Harbin]]\n[[Category:Australian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:British people of German descent]]\n[[Category:British people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Australian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:British Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Australian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Australian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:British philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Australian billionaires]]\n[[Category:British billionaires]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Gregory the Great]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Sir]]\n| name               = Michael Hintze\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of St. Gregory the Great|GCSG]], [[Order of Australia|AM]]\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              =\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!--only use if different from name-->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1953|07|27}}\n| birth_place        = [[Harbin]], China\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| monuments          = \n| residence          = [[United Kingdom]]\n| nationality        = \n| alma_mater         = {{Unbulleted list|[[University of Sydney]]|{{nowrap|[[University of New South Wales]]}}|[[Harvard Business School]]}}\n| occupation         = Asset manager\n| years_active       = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = [[CQS (Hedge Fund)|CQS]]\n| net_worth          = {{increase}} {{GBP}}1.5 billion <small>(2019, Sunday Times Rich List)</small>\n| height             = <!-- {{height|cm=}} -->\n| weight             = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} -->\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = Dorothy\n| children           = Four\n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n| allegiance                = {{flag|Australia}}\n| branch                    = [[Australian Army]]\n| serviceyears              = 3 years minimum service\n| rank                      = Captain}}\n}}\n\n'''Sir Michael Hintze''', [[Order of St. Gregory the Great|GCSG]], [[Order of Australia|AM]] (born 27 July 1953) is a British-Australian businessman, philanthropist and [[Conservative Party UK|Conservative Party]] patron, based in the United Kingdom.\n\nAccording to the 2019 ''[[Sunday Times Rich List]]'', Hintze is worth \u00a31.5 billion, an increase of \u00a3120 million from 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sunday-times-rich-list-2019-profiles-101-148-alan-sugar-dx9qlpwcp|title=Rich List 2019: profiles 101-148=, featuring Alan Sugar|last=Times|first=The Sunday|date=2019-05-12|access-date=2019-07-11|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> In the 2016 [[Forbes|''Forbes'' magazine]] list of The World's Billionaires, he was the world's 1,011th richest person, with a [[net worth]] of approximately {{USD}}1.8&nbsp;billion.<ref name=Forbes2016>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/michael-hintze/ |title=Michael Hintze|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=9 June 2016|date=2016}}</ref><ref name=DMailBio/><ref name=Telg8821348/> \n\n==Early life==\nAfter his grandparents fled from Russia after the 1917 [[Bolshevik revolution]],<ref name=Telg8821348/> he was born in the Chinese city of [[Harbin]]. After [[Mao Zedong]] and the [[Chinese Communist Party]] took over power, his refugee parents left for Australia.<ref name=DMailBio/>\n\nRaised by his secretary mother in Sydney, he was educated at [[St Leo's Catholic College|St Leo's College Wahroonga]] the local [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]] school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/work-and-careers/management/billionaire-michael-hintze-is-betting-on-the-farm-20180306-h0x2af|title=Billionaire Michael Hintze is betting on the farm |publisher=Australian Financial Review|date=2018-04-18}}</ref> He then studied at the [[University of Sydney]] where he obtained a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] degree in physics in 1975 and a [[Bachelor of Engineering|BE]] degree in engineering in 1977, residing at [[St John's College, University of Sydney|St John's College]]. He also holds an [[Master of Science|MSc]] degree in Acoustics from the [[University of New South Wales]], an [[Master of Business|MBA]] degree from [[Harvard Business School]], an Honorary Doctorate of Business from the University of New South Wales, and a DEng (honoris causa) from the University of Sydney.<ref>{{cite web |title=From engineer to philanthropist and global businessman |url=https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/News/engineer-philanthropist-and-global-businessman |website=Engineers Australia |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn graduation, he joined the [[Australian Army]] for three years, rising to the rank of [[Captain (armed forces)|captain]].<ref name=DMailBio/> Following that, he worked as an [[electrical engineering|electrical]] [[design engineer]] for Civil and Civic Pty Ltd. in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://michael-hintze.com/bio/|website=www.michael-hintze.com|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMoving to New York to train in financial services, he worked for [[Salomon Brothers]] as a fixed income trader and at [[Credit Suisse First Boston]]. Relocating to London with them, he then joined [[Goldman Sachs]], where his ultimate position was Co-head of the UK Shares Product. He left the firm in 1995.\n\n=== CQS ===\nIn 1999 he launched his own asset management firm, [[CQS (Hedge Fund)|CQS]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cqscapital.com/ |title=CQS - CQS is a global multi-strategy asset management firm |website=Cqscapital.com |date= |accessdate=2016-06-30}}</ref> and has been cited in the press as one of the highest paid people in the [[City of London]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/news/article.html?in_article_id=404355&in_page_id=2 |title=Hedge fund boss with a '\u00a360m pay packet' |work=This is money |date= |accessdate= |publisher= |author= |location= }}</ref> Hintze was ranked No. 5 on [[Financial News]]' FN100 Most Influential list in the hedge fund category.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/fn100/2012#Hedge%20funds |title=Financial News FN100 Most Influential List |work=eFinancial News  |date= |accessdate= |publisher= |author= |location= }}</ref> CQS Asset Management, which has been described as \"one of the world's leading credit market players\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c5ddc4f4-0ab2-11df-b35f-00144feabdc0.html#axzz1xfGTDwcl |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=27 January 2010 |title=CQS warns over housing market and economy |accessdate=14 June 2012 }}</ref> has assets under management reported at $11&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hedgefundsreview.com/hedge-funds-review/interview/1899531/cqs-diversified-fund-segregated-portfolio-alpha-cqs |title=Archived copy |accessdate=14 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223234127/http://www.hedgefundsreview.com/hedge-funds-review/interview/1899531/cqs-diversified-fund-segregated-portfolio-alpha-cqs |archivedate=23 December 2011 }}</ref>  The CQS Directional Opportunities Fund, which is managed by Hintze, was ranked #3 on [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]'s list of the 100 top-performing large hedge funds for 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-01-03/the-100-top-performing-large-hedge-funds.html | work=Bloomberg | title=The 100 Top-Performing Large Hedge Funds |date=3 January 2013  |accessdate=2016-06-30 |publisher= |author= |location= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Hintze's CQS received awards for the \"Best Hedge Fund Manager Overall,\" \"Best Hedge Fund Manager in Credit,\" and \"Best Multi-Hedge Fund Manager\" at the [[Financial News]] Awards for Excellence in Institutional Hedge Fund Management.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2013-05-09/financial-news-hedge-fund-awards-2013-winners-michael-hintze-cqs?ref=email_41688 |work=[[Financial News]] |date=4 June 2013 |title=Hat-trick for CQS at FN Hedge Fund Awards |accessdate= |publisher= |author= |location= }}</ref> CQS was reported to be on the opposite side<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-05-15/news/31711565_1_jpmorgan-chase-hedge-funds-jpmorgan-trade |work=The Economic Times |date=15 May 2012 |title=Hedge funds eye further profits from JPMorgan losses |accessdate=14 June 2012 }} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> of the infamous [[2012 JPMorgan Chase trading loss|JPMorgan trade]] by Bruno Iksil, nicknamed the London Whale, in which JPMorgan lost an estimated $2&nbsp;billion. The total gains by CQS are unknown.<ref>Fletcher, Laurence; Wilkes, Tommy. [https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-jpmorgan-hedgefunds-idUSLNE84E01T20120515 \"Hedge funds eye further profits from JPMorgan losses\"], ''Reuters'', 15 May 2012. Accessed 12 July 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, it was reported that CQS's main fund increased by 30%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/richest-hedge-fund-managers-in-britain-sunday-times-rich-list-2018-5|title=These are the 13 richest hedge fund managers in Britain \u2014 all worth more than \u00a3400 million|last=Martin|first=Will|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\nHintze is credited by veteran economic commentator and journalist [[Alex Brummer]] with warning about the state of [[UK banking]], the outlook for the [[UK housing market]], and the scale of [[toxic-debt]] on the balance sheets of UK banks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/news/article-2025039/ALEX-BRUMMER-Euro-banks-facing-crunch.html |work=[[This is Money]]/[[Daily Mail]]|date=11 August 2011 |author=Brummer, Alex |author-link=Alex Brummer |title=Euro banks facing a crunch |accessdate=14 June 2012}}</ref> \n\n===Professional Appointments===\nDue to his expertise in global financial markets, Hintze has been tapped to sit on a number of boards and government panels. He was appointed by the [[Department of the Treasury (Australia)|Australian Treasury]] to sit on a four-person International Advisory Panel to support the Financial Systems Inquiry (FSI), which is focused on issues impacting [[Australia's economy]] such as technological change, Australia's global competitiveness and offshore regulatory frameworks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.financialstandard.com.au/news/view/38843954 |title=Michael Hintze to join Financial Systems Inquiry |work=Financial Standard |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nHintze was appointed by [[Pope Francis]] to the board of the Vatican Bank (officially known as the [[Institute for the Works of Religion]]).<ref name=\"VIS 2014\">{{cite web | url=http://visnews-en.blogspot.co.at/2014/07/new-economic-framework-for-holy-see.html | title=New Economic Framework for the Holy See | publisher=[[Vatican Information Service]] | date=9 July 2014 | accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref>  According to ValueWalk, \u201cThe addition of Hintze is viewed as a significant positive for the Vatican\u201d due to the fact that he is a \u201cno nonsense manager with deep insight into a broad range of international finance matters.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valuewalk.com/2014/07/hintze-cqs-vatican/ |title=As Hintze Tapped For \"Gods Work,\" CQS Funds Perform |work=ValueWalk |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK, Hintze was also appointed to serve on the Fair and Effective Markets Review, a joint review by the [[HM Treasury|Treasury]], the [[Bank of England]] and the [[Financial Conduct Authority]] (FCA) focused on raising standards of conduct in the financial system.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fair-and-effective-markets-review-announced-by-chancellor-of-the-exchequer |title=Fair and Effective Markets Review announced by Chancellor of the Exchequer |website=Gov.uk |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> He also sits on the Finance & Audit Committee of the Duchy of Cornwall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://michael-hintze.com/bio/|website=www.michael-hintze.com|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Farming==\nIn 2007, Hintze established MH Premium Farms (MHPF)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mhpremiumfarms.com/|website=MH Premium Farms|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref>, a group of agriculture companies based mainly in Australia. MHPF now owns more than 20 properties<ref>{{cite web|title=Properties|url=http://mhpremiumfarms.com/properties/#|website=MH Premium Farms|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref> in eastern Australia, covering a total area of more than 70,000 hectares. The properties offer a broad portfolio including: fat lambs, wool and cattle; broad acre cropping of cereals and oilseeds; irrigated cotton and sugar.\n\nSustainable agricultural processes and environmental responsibility are core facets of MHPF\u2019s approach.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Williamson |first1=Christine |title=CQS chief plows his support into sustainable farm management |url=https://www.pionline.com/article/20170206/PRINT/302069988/cqs-chief-plows-his-support-into-sustainable-farm-management |accessdate=25 February 2020 |publisher=Pensions & Investments |date=6 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nWith his wife Dorothy, Hintze set up the Hintze Family Charitable Foundation, which has given significant and wide-ranging philanthropic support to over 200 causes, focusing mainly on health, education, armed services, culture, and the arts.<ref name=DMailBio/>\n\nIn the area of culture and the arts, notable donations include enabling the restoration of [[Michelangelo]]'s frescoes in the [[Cappella Paolina|Pauline Chapel]] at the [[Apostolic Palace|Vatican]] and in 2014 donating \u00a35 million to the [[Natural History Museum, London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-27319973 |title=Natural History Museum receives \u00a35m donation |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=2016-06-30}}</ref> The donation to the Natural History Museum <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-27319973 |title=BBC, 8 May 2014 \"Natural History Museum receives \u00a35m donation\" |accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> is the biggest single donation received by the museum in 133 years (in other words, since 1881 when the Museum opened to the public for the first time). The gift will be used in part to fund programmes to study problems that threaten Earth's biodiversity such as the maintenance of delicate ecosystems and the impacts of environmental pollution, as well as the battle against diseases such as malaria.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.nhm.ac.uk/Press-releases/The-Natural-History-Museum-receives-5-million-donation-13a.aspx |title=Natural History Museum, 8 May 2014 \"The Natural History Museum receives \u00a35 million donation\" |accessdate=27 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140627120826/http://media.nhm.ac.uk/Press-releases/The-Natural-History-Museum-receives-5-million-donation-13a.aspx |archivedate=27 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The museum's Central Hall has since been renamed 'Hintze Hall'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/dinosaurs/10814292/Dippy-the-Natural-History-Museum-diplodocus-could-be-moved.html |title=Dippy the Natural History Museum diplodocus could be moved |website=Telegraph.co.uk |accessdate=2016-06-30}}</ref>\n\nProjects in culture and the arts have also enabled the refurbishment of the V&A's Sculpture Galleries, named the Dorothy and Michael Hintze Galleries,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vam.ac.uk/page/s/sculpture-galleries/ |title=Victoria & Albert Museum Sculpture Galleries |accessdate=2017-06-19}}</ref> and have included sponsorship of an iconic exhibition of [[Raphael]]'s Tapestries from the [[Sistine Chapel]] at the [[V&A]], and a \u00a32 million donation to the [[National Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.philanthropyuk.org/news/2011-01-28/hintze-family-charitable-foundation-donates-\u00a32m-national-gallery |title=Philanthropy UK, 28 January 2011 \"Hintze Family Foundation donates \u00a32m to National Gallery\" |accessdate=14 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229113851/http://www.philanthropyuk.org/news/2011-01-28/hintze-family-charitable-foundation-donates-%C2%A32m-national-gallery |archive-date=29 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The donation to the National Gallery has been used in part to fund refurbishment, including the installation of new technology to reduce the gallery's running costs and carbon footprint.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/jan/20/michael-hintze-donation-national-gallery |title=The Guardian, 20 January 2011 \"Hedge fund founder Michael Hintze donates \u00a32m to National Gallery\" | location=London | first=Mark |last=Brown |date=20 January 2011}}</ref> Support has also been provided to the British Museum and the National Portrait Gallery. The Hintze Family Charitable Foundation is also listed as a Life Benefactor Donor to the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/51800/information-for-current-members/life-benefactor-donors.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=29 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729004752/http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/51800/information-for-current-members/life-benefactor-donors.html |archivedate=29 July 2012 }}</ref> Through CQS and the Hintze Family Charitable Foundation he provided funding to create a 'theatre in the round' at the [[Old Vic]] in London, amongst other significant support. He also came to the aid of [[Wandsworth Museum]], which was facing imminent closure by offering a \u00a32 million rescue package.\n\nIn the area of health, he co-chaired Clapham's [[Trinity Hospice]] campaign for a new in-patient centre which has now been completed. Hintze gave a $1 million gift to the [[University of Sydney]]'s Charles Perkins Centre, which focuses on turning medical research into viable treatments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sydney.edu.au/news/84.html?newsstoryid=11487 |title=Three major donations take University of Sydney $16 million closer to $600 million fundraising goal|website=Sydney.edu.au |date=2013-05-04 |accessdate=2016-06-30}}</ref> He has also provided support to the Evelina Children's Hospital.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blackhurst|first1=Chris|title=Interview: Sir Michael Hintze, CQS Hedge Fund - charity is a way of life for accomplished money-maker who enjoys giving it away|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/business/markets/interview-sir-michael-hintze-cqs-hedge-fund-charity-is-a-way-of-life-for-accomplished-money-maker-9874855.html|accessdate=9 January 2018|agency=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nHis support for the armed services has included donations to The Royal Navy & Royal Marines Charity. Among other initiatives, this has included providing funding to support serving personnel and their families.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fundraising.co.uk/2013/12/18/sir-michael-hintze-donate-500000-navys-charity/#.WRq6jFPytE4 |title=Sir Michael Hintze to donate \u00a3500,000 to the Navy's charity |publisher=UK Fundraising|accessdate=2017-05-16}}</ref> He has also provided support to the Black Stork Charity to help construct one of the most advanced centres for rehabilitation of injured military personnel in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thednrc.org.uk/whats-happening-on-now/we-are-fundraising/how-have-we-got-there.aspx|website=DNRC|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn education, among major donations, he has established the chair of International Security at the University of Sydney<ref>{{cite web|title=CENTRE FOR INTERNATIONAL SECURITY STUDIES|url=http://sydney.edu.au/arts/ciss/|website=University of Sydney|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> and supported the University of Oxford Centre for Astrophysical Surveys,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.physics.ox.ac.uk/research/astrophysics/oxford-centre-for-astrophysical-surveys |title=Oxford Centre for Astrophysical Surveys |accessdate=2017-06-19}}</ref> where the Annual Hintze Lecture has been established.\n\nFunding was provided for the construction of a residential wing at St. John\u2019s College at the University of Sydney, which was named the Hintze Building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stjohnscollege.edu.au/history/ |title=History - St John's College |website=stjohnscollege.edu.au |accessdate=2017-05-16}}</ref> Hintze has also donated $1 million to the [[University of New South Wales]] (UNSW) for a new lecture theatre.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Offner |url=http://newsroom.unsw.edu.au/news/science-technology/sir-michael-hintzes-1-million-gift |title=Sir Michael Hintze's $1 million gift &#124; UNSW Newsroom |website=Newsroom.unsw.edu.au |date=2013-09-13 |accessdate=2016-06-30}}</ref> The donation was made in honour of his father, Michael Hintze senior, who is also a UNSW alumnus. Gifts have also been made to Harvard University<ref>{{cite web|title=Donors and Their Gifts|url=https://alumni.harvard.edu/college/college-giving/gift-planning/donors-and-gifts?page=1|website=Harvard}}</ref> ($10m) and Princeton University, where a Professorship for the Arts has been established in his wife's maiden name (Dorothy Krauklis)<ref>{{cite web|title=Supporters|url=http://arts.princeton.edu/people/supporters/|website=Lewis Center for the Arts - Princeton|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref>.\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that Hintze is a donor to the [[Global Warming Policy Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Readfearn|first=Graham|title=Michael Hintze revealed as funder of Lord Lawson's climate thinktank|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/mar/27/tory-donor-climate-sceptic-thinktank|accessdate=27 March 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 March 2012|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropic Positions & Recognitions===\nHintze currently serves as a trustee of the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/prime-minister-appoints-sir-michael-hintze-bjorn-saven-sir-peter-stothard-and-rachel-wang-as-trustees-of-the-national-portrait-gallery |title=Prime Minister Appoints Sir Michael Hintze, Bj\u00f6rn Sav\u00e9n, Sir Peter Stothard and Rachel Wang as Trustees of the National Portrait Gallery. |website=gov.uk |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> the [[Institute of Economic Affairs]], the University of Sydney Trust, as a Member of the Harvard Business School Board of Dean\u2019s Advisors\u2019, and as Senior Vice Patron of the Royal Navy & Royal Marines Charity.<ref>{{cite web|title=SENIOR VICE PATRON - SIR MICHAEL HINTZE AM|url=https://www.rnrmc.org.uk/senior-vice-patron-sir-michael-hintze-am|website=Royal Navy & Royal Marines Charity|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> He was formerly chairman of the [[The Prince's Foundation for Building Community|Prince's Foundation for Building Community]].\n\nHintze was formerly a trustee of the [[National Gallery]], where he assisted in securing Titian\u2019s [[Diana and Actaeon (Titian)|''Diana and Actaeon'']] for the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/paintings/titian-diana-and-actaeon |title=Diana and Actaeon |website=nationalgallery.org.uk |accessdate=2017-05-16}}</ref>  He was initially appointed to the National Gallery's Board of Trustees by then [[Labour Party UK|Labour Party]] Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] in 2008. He was later reappointed by Conservative Party Prime Minister [[David Cameron]].\n\nIn recognition of their charitable contributions in support of the arts, Michael Hintze and his wife Dorothy received the Prince of Wales Medal for Arts Philanthropy in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsandbusiness.org.uk/Central/volunteering/prince-of-wales-medal/michael_and_dorothy_hintze.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=21 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801044751/http://www.artsandbusiness.org.uk/Central/volunteering/prince-of-wales-medal/michael_and_dorothy_hintze.aspx |archivedate=1 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHintze was invited to the Chancellor's Court of Benefactors<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.campaign.ox.ac.uk/donate/recognising-your-gift |title=University of Oxford. |website=campaign.ox.ac.uk |accessdate=2017-06-19}}</ref> for his support of the University of Oxford.\n\nHe was named to the 2017 Debrett\u2019s 500 List, in recognition of his considerable philanthropic contributions in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|title=Debrett's 500 List: Philanthropists & Activists|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/debretts-500-list-philanthropists-activists/|accessdate=9 January 2018|publisher=Telegraph}}</ref> He was also named to the Evening Standard\u2019s \u201cProgress 1000\u201d list of \u201cLondon\u2019s most influential people,\u201d citing his philanthropic contributions and business success.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Progress 1000: London's most influential people 2017 - Capitalisers: Business|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/the1000/the-progress-1000-londons-most-influential-people-2017-capitalisers-business-a3655286.html|accessdate=9 January 2018|publisher=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative Party donations===\nIn 2006, at the time of the [[Cash for Peerages]] allegations concerning the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], Hintze voluntarily revealed he was one of the previously anonymous patrons who had made loans to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iaindale.blogspot.com/2006/03/exclusive-loan-tory-chooses-this-blog.html |title=Iain Dale'S Diary: Exclusive: Loan Tory Chooses This Blog To Go Public |website=Iaindale.blogspot.com |date=2006-03-25 |accessdate=2016-06-30}}</ref> In 2011 his known loans and donations to the party totalled around \u00a34 million.<ref name=DMailBio/> In the five months to September 2011 he donated \u00a331,000, enough to grant him membership of the Conservative Treasurers' Group, the second highest rung on the party's donor's ladder, which allows its members access to senior Conservative figures through a series of lunches, receptions and campaign launches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thebureauinvestigates.com/2011/10/17/george-osborne-gets-almost-twice-that-of-liam-fox-from-michael-hintze/|title=George Osborne gets almost twice that of Liam Fox from Michael Hintze|date=17 October 2011 |author1=Oldroyd, Rachel |author2=McClenaghan, Maeve|accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Conservative Party were in opposition, Hintze disclosed that he had donated to [[George Osborne]], [[David Willetts]], [[Liam Fox]], [[Theresa May]], [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]], [[Adam Holloway]], and [[Boris Johnson]].<ref name=DMailBio/> In addition, CQS made non-cash donations to [[William Hague]], Liam Fox, and George Osborne.<ref name=DMailBio/> In May 2008, [[David Cameron]] declared a donation from Hintze to the Conservative Party that was used to pay for drinks receptions for Tory MPs and their partners.<ref>Stratton, Allegra. [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/sep/29/partyfunding.toryconference \"Short-sellers are revealed as substantial party donors\"], ''The Guardian'', 28 September 2008. Accessed 12 July 2016.</ref> In March 2008, Hintze paid for a private jet to ferry Cameron and Osborne from Newcastle to [[Biggin Hill]] after the Conservative Party conference.<ref name=DMailBio/>\n\nIn October 2011, it was revealed that [[Adam Werritty]], a close friend and business associate of then [[Secretary of State for Defence]] Liam Fox, was provided with a free desk by Hintze at CQS's London base as part of his \u00a329,000 donation to Fox's charity ''[[The Atlantic Bridge]]''.<ref name=Telg8821348>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/8821348/Michael-Hintze-the-millionaire-Tory-donor-who-once-said-the-more-you-give-the-more-you-get.html|title=Michael Hintze: the millionaire Tory donor who once said: the more you give, the more you get|publisher=The Telegraph|date=18 October 2011|accessdate=18 October 2011|location=London|first=Tim|last=Ross}}</ref><ref name=\"Mirror\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2011/10/09/liam-fox-on-the-run-in-storm-over-ex-flatmate-adviser-115875-23476094/ |title=Liam Fox on the run in storm over ex-flatmate 'adviser'|publisher=Mirror |date=9 October 2011 |accessdate=11 October 2011}}</ref> Hintze also supplied a private jet for Fox and Werritty to fly from the United States to London in May 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/8821209/Liam-Foxs-friend-Adam-Werritty-linked-to-Conservative-donor.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Holly | last=Watt | title=Liam Fox's friend Adam Werritty linked to Conservative donor | date=11 October 2011}}</ref> These disclosures led to the resignation of Liam Fox (who was then [[Secretary of State for Defence]]) and the dismissal of Hintze's then-charity adviser, Oliver Hylton.<ref name=Readfearn2012>{{cite news|last1=Readfearn|first1=Graham|title=Michael Hintze revealed as funder of Lord Lawson's climate thinktank|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/mar/27/tory-donor-climate-sceptic-thinktank|accessdate=8 June 2014|work=The Guardian|date=27 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHe was made a [[Order of St. Gregory|Knight Commander of the Papal Order of St. Gregory]] (KCSG) by [[Pope Benedict XVI]] in 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://advance.org/michael-hintze/ |title=Sir Michael Hintze AM |website=Advance.org |date= |accessdate=2016-06-30}}</ref> and was later was elevated to a Knight Grand Cross of the same Order (GCSG).\n\nIn January 2013, Hintze was appointed [[Order of Australia|Member of the Order of Australia]] (AM) for his \"significant service to the community through philanthropic contributions to organisations supporting the arts, health and education.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/australia-day-honours-list/story-e6frg6n6-1226562330797|title=Australia Day Honours List 2013|work=The Australian|date=26 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the United Kingdom's [[2013 Birthday Honours]] for services to the arts.<ref name=gaz31712>{{London Gazette|issue=60534|supp=y|page=1|date=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"HM Birthday Honours 2013\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/206698/Birthday_Honours_List_2013.pdf|title=Birthday Honours List 2013|accessdate=14 June 2013|date=14 June 2013|publisher=HM Government}}</ref> He received his accolade on 23 October 2013 by [[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]] at Buckingham Palace.\n\n==Personal life==\nMarried to American citizen Dorothy, whom he met at Harvard,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/15/style/dorothy-e-krauklis-is-married-to-michael-hintze.html \"Dorothy E. Krauklis Is Married to Michael Hintze\"], ''The New York Times'', 15 July 1984. Accessed 12 July 2016.</ref> the couple have four children, partially educated at British private schools.<ref name=DMailBio>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2050331/Michael-Hintze-Hedge-fund-baron-David-Camerons-sugar-daddy.html#ixzz1b88dXKaA|title=Hedge fund baron Hintze \u2013 sugar daddy to Cameron and Co|author1=Gladdis, Keith |author2=Martin, Arthur |author3=Pendlebury, Richard|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=18 October 2011|accessdate=18 October 2011|location=London}}</ref> Hintze is a [[Roman Catholic]].<ref name=RC>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2568073/SEBASTIAN-SHAKESPEARE-Billionaire-Tory-donor-pulls-plug-Cameron.html|title=Billionaire Tory donor pulls plug on Cameron|work=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=26 February 2014|location=London|first=Sebastian|last=Shakespeare|date=26 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Wealth rankings===\n{{columns-start}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Year\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:40%;\"| ''[[Business Review Weekly|BRW]]''<br>[[BRW Rich 200|Rich 200]]\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:40%;\"| ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]''<br>[[List of Australians by net worth|Australia's 50 Richest]]\n|-\n! Rank\n! [[Net worth]] ({{AUD}})\n! Rank\n! [[Net worth]] ({{USD}})\n|-\n| 2011<ref name=\"BRW2011\">{{cite news|url=http://www.brw.com.au/Page/Uuid/8ab8af52-7ea0-11e0-9add-765096dd6fc5 |title=Passport Power |work=BRW Rich 200 Wealth Index |location=Australia |date=25 May 2011 |accessdate=2 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110092252/http://www.brw.com.au/Page/Uuid/8ab8af52-7ea0-11e0-9add-765096dd6fc5 |archivedate=10 November 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2011\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2011/78/australia-billionaires-11_land.html |title=2011 Australia's 40 Richest |accessdate=8 February 2011 |work=Forbes Asia |date=2 February 2011 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $0.614&nbsp;billion {{profit}} \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|15}} {{loss}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.40&nbsp;billion {{gain}}\n|-\n| 2012<ref name=\"BRW2012\">{{cite news |url=http://www.afr.com/business/the-list--brw-rich-200-2012-20120523-jyjj3 |title=The list - BRW Rich 200 2012 |work=[[Financial Review]] |date=23 May 2012 |accessdate=9 June 2016 |editor=Stensholt, John |location=Australia }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2012\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2012/78/australia-billionaires-12_rank.html |title=2012 Australia's 40 Richest |accessdate=3 June 2012 |work=Forbes Asia |date=1 February 2012 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|40}} \n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $0.81&nbsp;billion {{gain}} \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|16}} {{loss}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.40&nbsp;billion {{steady}}\n|-\n| 2013<ref name=\"BRW2013\">{{cite news |url=http://www.afr.com/leadership/brw-lists/brw-rich-200-list-2013-20160303-gn9dxc |title=BRW Rich 200 List 2013 |work=[[Financial Review]] |date=May 2013 |accessdate=9 June 2016 |editor=Stensholt, John |location=Australia }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/gina-rinehart-tops-forbes-australian-rich-list/story-e6frg8zx-1226566120991 |title=Gina Rinehart tops Forbes' Australian rich list  |agency=AAP |author= |work=The Australian |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2013\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/australia-billionaires/list/|title=2013 Australia's 50 Richest|accessdate=23 May 2013|work=Forbes Asia|date=1 February 2013 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|43}} {{decrease}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $0.86&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|16}} {{steady}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.55&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|-\n| 2014<ref name=\"BRW2014\">{{cite news |url=http://www.afr.com/leadership/brw-lists/brw-rich-200-list-2014-20160303-gn9do8 |title=BRW Rich 200 List 2014 |work=[[Financial Review]] |date=27 June 2014 |accessdate=9 June 2016 |editor=Stensholt, John |location=Australia }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.afr.com/news/rinehart-on-top-palmer-down-on-forbes-rich-list-20140130-iy5uy |title=Rinehart on top, Palmer down on Forbes rich list |author=Rollason, Adam |work=Financial Review |location=Australia |date=30 January 2014 |accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/australia-billionaires/list/|title=2014 Australia's 50 Richest|accessdate=30 June 2014|work=Forbes Asia|date=January 2014 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|23}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.37&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|15}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.70&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|-\n| 2015<ref name=\"BRW2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.afr.com/leadership/brw-lists/brw-rich-200-list-2015-20160303-gn98ff|title=BRW Rich 200 List 2015 |work=[[Financial Review]] |date=May 2015 |accessdate=9 June 2016 |editor=Stensholt, John |location=Australia }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/australia-billionaires/list/#tab:overall|title=2015 Australia's 50 Richest|accessdate=10 June 2015|work=Forbes Asia|date=March 2015 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|21}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.75&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|15}} {{steady}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.90&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|-\n| 2016<ref name=\"Forbes2016\"/><ref name=BRW2016>{{cite journal|url=http://www.afr.com/leadership/brw-lists/brw-rich-200-list-2016-20160526-gp4ejn|title=BRW Rich 200 list 2016 |journal=[[Financial Review]]|location=Australia|date=27 May 2016|accessdate=9 June 2016|editor=Stensholt, John}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|37}} {{decrease}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.32&nbsp;billion {{decrease}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|13}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.80&nbsp;billion {{decrease}}\n|-\n| 2017<ref name=\"BRW2017\">{{cite news |url=https://www.afr.com/leadership/afr-lists/rich-list/financial-review-rich-list-2017-20170525-gwcvr6|title=BRW Rich 200 List 2017 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/australia-billionaires/list/#tab:overall_search:hintze|title=2017 Australia's 50 Richest|accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|24}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $1.98&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|17}} {{decrease}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $2.3&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|-\n| 2018<ref name=\"AFR2018\">{{cite news |url=https://www.afr.com/brand/afr-magazine/rich-list-overview-20180413-h0yqo5|title=AFR Rich List 2018 |accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/australia-billionaires/list/#tab:overall_search:hintze|title=2017 Australia's 50 Richest|accessdate=8 August 2018 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|22}} {{increase}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| $2.56&nbsp;billion {{increase}}\n|}\n{{column}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!cols